'''Kenji Joel Gorré''' (born 29 September 1994) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|winger]] for Israeli club [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.|Maccabi Haifa]]. Born in the Netherlands, he represents the [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao national team]]. He is the son of former professional footballer [[Dean Gorré]].

==Club career==
===Youth career===
Born in [[Spijkenisse]], Netherlands, Gorré lived in Netherlands before moving to England, when his father transferred to [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] when he was four<ref name="KGMEN">{{cite news|title=Kenji going Dutch|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/local-news/kenji-going-dutch-885076|work=Manchester Evening News|date=12 March 2010|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> and lived in England ever since.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gorré: 'De Nederlandse stijl past mij goed'|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/gorre-de-nederlandse-stijl-past-mij-goed.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=nl|date=9 July 2015|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gorré: 'Voor het eerst in mijn leven Sinterklaas gevierd'|url=http://www.vi.nl/premium-promo/gorre-voor-het-eerst-in-mijn-leven-sinterklaas-gevierd.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=nl|date=23 January 2016|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> Gorré attended [[North Cestrian Grammar School]].<ref name="KGMEN"/> Gorré's decision to play football was supported by his parents.<ref name="KGMEN"/>

In 2002, Gorré moved from [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester City Academy]] to [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United Academy]]. When Gorré was fifteen, Gorré became a transfer target from [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Chelsea Trying To Poach Manchester United Starlet Kenji Gorre – Report|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/9/english-football/2009/03/19/1163815/chelsea-trying-to-poach-manchester-united-starlet-kenji |publisher=Goal.com|date=19 March 2009|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> Despite, Gorré remained at the club and two years later, on 26 July 2011, Gorré scored in a 7–0 win over County Tyrone in the [[SuperCupNI|Milk Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Manchester United hammer Co Tyrone in Milk Cup|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/14300197|access-date=18 July 2016|work=BBC Sport|date=26 July 2011}}</ref> The following month, Gorré began to start his first year scholars at the academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/The-Academy/Academy-News/2011/Jul/united-first-year-scholars-intake.aspx|title=Reds draft in scholars|publisher=Manchester United F.C.|date=8 August 2011|access-date=18 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303225710/http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/The-Academy/Academy-News/2011/Jul/united-first-year-scholars-intake.aspx|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

Then in February 2013, Gorré went on trial at [[Scottish Premier League]] champions [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]], but he did not sign on a permanent basis.<ref>{{cite news|title=Celtic manager Neil Lennon assesses winger Kenji Gorre|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/scotland/21298293|work=BBC Sport|date=1 February 2013|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> This came after Gorré was released from the [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United Academy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Veseli heads list of released United players |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/veseli-heads-list-released-manchester-4187499 |work=Manchester Evening News |date=7 June 2013 |access-date=18 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304035944/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/veseli-heads-list-released-manchester-4187499 |archive-date= 4 March 2016 }}</ref>

===Swansea City===
In March 2013, Gorré began training with [[Premier League]] side [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]]. Gorré made an impressive performance at the trial and convinced the Swansea City management to give him a one-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/new-life-kenji-gorre-man-18008351|title=The new life of Kenji Gorre, the Man Utd kid who promised so much at Swansea City as addiction nearly cost him everything|website=walesonline.co.uk|publisher=Media Wales Ltd|date=2 April 2020|access-date=9 July 2021}}</ref>

Shortly signing for Swansea City, Gorré was featured in the pre-season [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] matches and scored two goals against [[Excelsior Maassluis|Excelsior]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/holland-excelsior-report-899650.aspx|title=FULL-TIME: Excelsior 1 Swansea City 5|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C.|date=7 July 2013|access-date=18 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910191257/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/holland-excelsior-report-899650.aspx|archive-date=10 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[VV Haaglandia|Haaglandia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/holland-haaglandia-report-906196.aspx|title=FULL-TIME: Haaglandia 0 Swansea City 10|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C.|date=10 July 2013|access-date=18 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910223736/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/holland-haaglandia-report-906196.aspx|archive-date=10 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Despite being given forty-six shirt,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/squad-numbers-13-14-938069.aspx|title=Squad numbers confirmed|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C.|date=23 July 2013|access-date=18 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822212734/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/squad-numbers-13-14-938069.aspx|archive-date=22 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Gorré was sent to the [[Swansea City A.F.C. Under-23s|Swansea City Reserves]] and played there throughout the 2013–14 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/gorre-targets-cup-success-1194603.aspx|title=Gorré targets cup success|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C.|date=25 November 2013|access-date=18 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210041348/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/gorre-targets-cup-success-1194603.aspx|archive-date=10 December 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 4 July 2014, Gorré signed a new two-year contract keeping him at the club until June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southwales-eveningpost.co.uk/Stephen-Kingsley-eyeing-Swansea-City-team-chance/story-21316059-detail/story.html |title=Stephen Kingsley eyeing Swansea City first team chance after arriving from Falkirk|publisher=southwales-eveningpost.co.uk |date=2 July 2014 |access-date=2 July 2014}}</ref> This came after when Gorré was offered a professional contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/youngsters-contract-extensions-1582928.aspx|title=Eight young Swansea City pros offered contract extensions|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C.|date=30 May 2014|access-date=18 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128112920/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/youngsters-contract-extensions-1582928.aspx|archive-date=28 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Later in the 2014–15 season, Gorré became the top scorer for [[Swansea City A.F.C. Under-23s|Swansea Under-21s]] during the [[2014–15 Professional U21 Development League#League 2|2014–15 Professional U21 Development League 2]] season,<ref>{{cite news|title=Who are Swansea City's silverware-winning youngsters and potential stars of the future? The Swans' next generation...|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/who-swansea-citys-silverware-winning-youngsters-9258421|publisher=Wales Online|date=14 May 2015|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> and scored twice as the Under-21s won the [[2014–15 Professional U21 Development League#League 2|league]] title.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/llewellyn-delighted-to-end-season-on-a-high-2455759.aspx |title=Llewellyn delighted to end season on a high|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C. |date=13 May 2015 |access-date=13 May 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150514160119/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/llewellyn-delighted-to-end-season-on-a-high-2455759.aspx |archive-date=14 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> After impressing for the Under-21s, Gorré made his professional debut for Swansea in a 1–0 [[Premier League]] loss away to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 24 May 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32770846 |title=Crystal Palace 1 Swansea City 0|work=BBC Sport |date=24 May 2015 |access-date=6 July 2015}}</ref>

On 6 July 2015, Gorré signed a new three-year contract with Swansea City, keeping him at the club until the summer of 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Swansea City: Kenji Gorre signs new three-year deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/33413194  |work=BBC Sport |date=6 July 2015}}</ref> Two days later, on 8 July 2015, Swansea City agreed a deal to loan Gorré out to Dutch side [[ADO Den Haag]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/gorre-joins-den-haag-on-loan-2530803.aspx|title=Young Swans forward Kenji Gorre joins Den Haag on loan|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C|date=8 July 2016|access-date=18 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709231754/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/gorre-joins-den-haag-on-loan-2530803.aspx|archive-date=9 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gorré made his ADO Den Haag debut as a 76th-minute substitute, and set up a goal from a free kick to goalkeeper, [[Martin Hansen (footballer)|Martin Hansen]], to score his [[List of goalscoring goalkeepers|first ever professional goal]], to earn his team a last-minute draw against [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/adogoalie-hansen-bezorgt-psv-kater-met-geniale-goal.htm |title=ADO-goalie Hansen bezorgt PSV kater met geniale goal |language=nl |date=11 August 2015 |publisher=[[Voetbal International]] |access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> However, six days later, Gorré was sent to the reserves to play against [[Heracles Almelo|Jong Heracles]] and in the 36th minute, he received a straight red card for a professional foul.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jong Heracles geeft voorsprong uit handen|url=http://www.tubantia.nl/sport/heracles/jong-heracles-geeft-voorsprong-uit-handen-1.5162553|publisher=Tubantia Official Website|language=nl|date=17 August 2015|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> After the match, KNVB decided against giving Gorré a game suspension.<ref>{{cite news|title=KNVB besluit ook Gorré niet te schorsen na rode kaart|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/knvb-besluit-ook-gorre-niet-te-schorsen-na-rode-kaart.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=nl|date=19 August 2015|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> However, Gorré went on to make five appearances, having spent the first half of the season at ADO Den Haag on the bench and on 30 January 2016, it was confirmed that Gorré had returned to Swansea City following his loan spell at ADO Den Haag.<ref>{{cite news|title=ADO laat Gorré per direct terugkeren naar Swansea|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/ado-laat-gorre-per-direct-terugkeren-naar-swansea.htm|publisher=Voetbal International|language=nl|date=30 January 2016|access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref>

Following his return from a loan at ADO Den Haag, Gorré returned to the club's reserves and scored on his return, in a 2–1 win over [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/swansea-city-under-21s-kenji-gorre-jefferson-montero-2994970.aspx|title=Gorre takes lesson from Montero's experience|publisher=Swansea City A.F.C.|date=8 March 2016|access-date=18 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405072003/http://www.swanseacity.net/news/article/swansea-city-under-21s-kenji-gorre-jefferson-montero-2994970.aspx|archive-date=5 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 29 July 2016, Gorré joined [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] on a six-month loan deal until January 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/sport/football/new-signing-gorre-to-add-dutch-of-class-to-cobblers-squad-1-7501472|title=Gorre to show dutch of class|publisher=Northampton Chronicle and Echo|date=29 July 2016}}</ref>

He was unable to break into the first team at Swansea, and despite being offered a new contract, he left the club at the end of his original three-year deal in June 2018.

===Nacional===
Following his release by Swansea, Gorré signed for [[Primeira Liga]] club [[C.D. Nacional|Nacional]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Swansea's Roque Mesa completes permanent switch to Sevilla |url=https://www.shropshirestar.com/sport/uk-sports/2018/06/27/swanseas-roque-mesa-completes-permanent-switch-to-sevilla/ |access-date=19 November 2020 |work=Shropshire Star |date=27 June 2018}}</ref>

In January 2019 he dropped a division to join [[Liga Portugal 2|LigaPro]] side [[G.D. Estoril Praia|Estoril]] on loan until the end of the remaining season.

=== Boavista ===
On 22 July 2021, [[Porto]]-based side [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]] announced the free signing of Gorré on a two-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=22 July 2022 |title=Kenji Gorré assina pelo Boavista FC |trans-title=Kenji Gorré signs for Boavista FC |url=https://boavistafc.pt/kenji-gorre-assina-pelo-boavista-fc/ |access-date=12 July 2023 |publisher=Boavista |language=pt-PT}}</ref>

=== Umm Salal ===
On 16 June 2023, after his contract with Boavista expired, Gorré signed a two-year deal with [[Qatar]]i club [[Umm Salal SC|Umm Salal]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=16 June 2023 |title=Depois do Boavista, Kenji Gorré ruma ao Umm-Salal, do Catar |trans-title=After Boavista, Kenji Gorré heads to Umm-Salal, from Qatar |url=https://www.zerozero.pt/news.php?id=488539 |access-date=12 July 2023 |website=zerozero.pt |language=pt}}</ref>

===Maccabi Haifa ===
On 17 July 2025, after his contract with Umm Salal expired, Gorré signed a tree-year with [[Israel]]i club [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.|Maccabi Haifa]].

==International career==
Gorré was born in the Netherlands to a Surinamese father, [[Dean Gorré]], and a Curaçaoan mother (Magali from [[The Real Housewives of Cheshire]]) and is eligible for all three national teams.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Gorré staat open voor Curaçao |url=https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/3934/gorre-staat-open-voor-curacao |date=2016-10-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626171817/https://www.telegraaf.nl/sport/3934/gorre-staat-open-voor-curacao/ |archive-date=2019-06-26 |access-date=2025-11-25 |website=[[De Telegraaf]] |language=nl}}</ref> Gorré is also eligible to play for [[England national football team|England]], citing having engaged in a minimum of five years education under the age of 18 within the territory of the relevant association.<ref name="KGMEN"/> Gorré was initially approached by the [[The Football Association|English FA]] before being selected by [[Royal Dutch Football Association|KNVB]] instead.<ref name="KGMEN"/> He never played for their youth team.

In November 2016, Gorré was called up to and played for the [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao national team]] in their [[Exhibition game#Association football|friendly]] against [[Eredivisie]] side [[SBV Excelsior|Excelsior]] in [[Rotterdam]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2016/11/09/bicentini-curacao-kan-wk-2022-halen/?npo_cc=126&npo_rnd=849028916|title=Bicentini: Curaçao kan WK 2022 halen {{!}} caribisch netwerk|website=caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl|access-date=11 November 2016}}</ref> In 2019, he was selected for the country's [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2019 Gold Cup]] squad and made his debut on 25 June 2019 in the last group game against [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]]. He came on as a substitute in the 70th minute for [[Jarchinio Antonia]], Curaçao equalised in added time to advance to the knock-out stage.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[CONCACAF]]|url=https://www.goldcup.org/en/gold-cup/game-detail/476783#tab_match=match-details|title=Jamaica v Curaçao game report|date=25 June 2019|access-date=26 June 2019|archive-date=26 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626231017/https://www.goldcup.org/en/gold-cup/game-detail/476783#tab_match=match-details|url-status=dead}}</ref>

